node.text: According to our Lifestyle Director @tarynwilliford, "there’s a difference between performative arranging, and problem-centric organizing solutions." Sure, a perfectly organized pantry where every nut and spice is decanted into gorgeously labeled jars and canisters is nice. But sometimes, in some small apartments, you just need to cram five pounds of stuff onto a two-inch bathroom shelf in a way that won’t make you perpetually 25 minutes late for everything. These kinds of solutions aren’t always worthy of a magazine spread, but they sure are worth stealing. Read about Taryn's recent favorite organizing tricks from tours (that are certainly worthy of stealing) via the link in our bio. (Image: @minettehand).

“I despise the current trend of attempting to turn these iconic San Francisco row houses into modernist glass-staired shells,” @allisonruthmuir says. “I thought about the house as if one family had lived here continuously since 1895 and kept layering with each generation.” It was this respect for the home’s rich history that shaped her design point of view, and resulted in a bright and exuberant style that Allison describes as “Victorian on Acid.” See the full space via the link in our bio. (Image: @estevancortez).

Maybe you scrimp and pinch to afford your dream heirloom rug. Or maybe you buy the most affordable rug you can find, resigned to the fact that kids and dogs and just living things in general will get it dirty over time. 
Whichever route you take, though, we bet you want to keep your rug looking nice for as long as possible. The goal isn’t forestalling the purchase of another but, more importantly, so that your rug doesn’t drag your space down with stains, marks, fading, or general grunginess. Instead, your spiffy rug should uplift your home (and the person who lives there, aka you!) to its full potential.

Fortunately, there’s one simple routine to help make that happen, click the link in our bio to read it! (Image: @linea.photo).
The weather outside is frightful, but this shed is so delightful. (via @kindredvintage).
Why, yes, we would love to sit on this pouf. (via @nest_twenty_eight).

This home in Ocean Grove, Australia gives us a new appreciation for concrete blocks. @bakaxe and Patricia, who runs @modernistaustralia, have a deep appreciation for  modernist architecture and design. So much so, that when they spied this home for sale online, they decided to move from Melbourne to Ocean Grove—situated on the surf coast—one and a half hours southwest of Melbourne. See the full tour of this dream home via the link in our bio. (Image: @nataliejeffcott).

Little fixes go a long way, but sometimes you just have to start from scratch. Just ask @toolboxdivas, whose kitchen was definitely past its prime. “I bought the house over eight years ago and the kitchen walls, ceiling, and tile backsplash were all blue,” Timisha says. “The cabinets were laminate and seriously dated.” Over 2 months, Timisha and her contractors created an entire new space. Bravo!!! See the full transformation via the link in our bio. (Image: @toolboxdivas).

We have a piece of news that is both VERY BIG and VERY SMALL... Small/Cool is BACK and better than ever.

The Small/Cool contest was invented in 2005 by Apartment Therapy’s founder and CEO Maxwell Ryan. The goal: to find the smallest, coolest, real-life space in NYC (and later on, the world!). The popular contest ran for more than 10 years before sunsetting in 2016.

Since then, we’ve heard from all of you loud and clear in our DMs, via email, in our comments, by carrier pigeons etc, "Bring Small/Cool back!" We are very good listeners, so here we are today announcing that this year the contest will make its long-awaited return. But first, we're kicking it off with our first-ever major live event in NYC: The Small/Cool Experience.

Stay tuned for more news about the Experience, the contest and more Small/Cool fun! The Experience is FREE. All you have to do is click the link in our bio to register. Welcome to Small/Cool 2020: Small spaces. Cool design. Big shopping. 🎉#SmallCoolNYC

We love a tiny house here at Apartment Therapy, so when we discovered @mandimakesminis we were immediately OBSESSED. These are the ultimate tiny houses, doll sized miniatures filled with incredibly realistic detail, all made by Mandi with painstaking care and attention. Read more about these miniatures via the link in our bio and check out @mandimakesminis for more inspiration! (via @mandimakesminis)

"This house has its own charm—the weird quirks, like crooked walls and cracks in the brick from previous tenants, and the tiny Harry Potter door under the stairs. It reminds us that there’s history in this home, and it has its own personality that we can work with and celebrate," explains DC-based photographer @raisaaziz about the charming space she shares with her husband Henry. They repurposed a lot of their old furniture items by spray painting them white to help them fit in this new space. See the full tour via the link in our bio. (Image: @fotosynthesis).

This Scottish home is positively bursting with bold colors. It also has one of our favorite things ever: built-in storage! The space is in a building that is in a UNESCO World Heritage Site in the West End of Edinburgh. "These buildings do cause a lot of headaches for modern living as they were originally built for a very different way of living, and so all the flats look identical on the outside. From the inside they’ve all been carved up very differently by various owners over the past 170 years!" explains @amyshirlawinteriors. See her full space via the link in our bio! (Image: @amyshirlawinteriors).
This is one foxy space 😉 (via @noelledowning).

Designer Anthony Gianacakos of @anthonygeorgehome didn’t let typical renter roadblocks prevent him from turning his kitchen into a small space sanctuary. In fact, he used them to his advantage, letting a recent trip to Lisbon—and the vibe of the coastal city—inspire this amazing transformation.

Naturally, a series of decorative paint jobs kicked things off. “The biggest thing a renter can do is add paint to the walls,” says Gianacakos. All it takes is speaking with your landlord to get permission. See the rest of his kitchen via the link in our bio. (Image: @martaxperez).

Ceramist and store owner Chela first started her creative career in textile design. After graduating in Melbourne in the early 2000s, she moved to New York, eventually working for big brands like Vera Wang and DKNY for five years. But after finding success in textiles, she turned her creative talents to ceramics, moving back to Melbourne and starting @takeawei, a company making “fun, functional, hand-crafted ceramics for home and hospitality.” She describes her space as being ‘maximalist wanting to be a minimalist," which makes perfect sense for this colorful, unique home. Click the link in our bio for more of this space. (Image: @nataliejeffcott).

Our News and Culture Editor, @tbellucci, wrote a love letter to gallery walls. "Art is personal. What we bring into our homes and have on our walls speaks about what we value, what’s important to us, and what we find beautiful, thought provoking, and worth memorializing. How you display it can be just as individual, because even though everybody’s heard of a gallery wall, there are a million and one ways to create one in your space," she writes. This unique, layered, wrapped gallery wall from @liz_kamarul is just one of many examples Tara featured in this piece. Click the link in our bio for more gallery wall inspiration. (Image: @liz_kamarul).
Is it Friday yet? (via @gingerdeb.house).

When it came to decorating the home @trinitymouzon and @isseykobori (co-founders of @golde) share, in Brooklyn’s Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood, the couple focused on how each item would contribute to their overall wellness. Color palettes are muted and soothing. The airiness of the small space is highlighted by minimal furnishings and lots of natural light, a perfect backdrop for two busy entrepreneurs who often work from home. See the full space via the link in our bio. (Image: @royancooper).

This Maine cottage has modern fixtures, while still maintaining its vintage appeal. Doesn't it look exactly how you'd want a cottage in Maine to look? Cozy, bright and incredibly charming. See the full space via the link in our bio. (Home: @ashorethingmaine; Image: @casmith_photography).

After living in her last apartment with a roommate for about six years, @emmaladyrose decided she was ready to purchase her first home. “I kind of thought I’d rent forever,” she says. “But when my roommate of six years and I decided we wanted to give living alone a go, I saw the insane rental prices of one bedrooms in New York and thought that if I could find a one bed to buy (on the cheaper end of the market), it might be worth doing that.” When she walked into this space, she says it felt like the couple who owned it before had made their renovations with her tastes in mind—and she fell in love. “Like with a life partner, when you know you know,” she says. See her full space via the linkn in our bio. (Image: @melanierieders).
The best light (via @fridlaa).

Julia Green is a former pharmaceutical industry executive with a passion for great design. Ten years ago, she set about a major career change and jumped into the world of interior styling. She founded @greenhouseinteriors along the way, which now represents over 30 brands and artists, many of which are found throughout her home. Click the link in our bio to see her full space. Warning: it WILL be hard to pick a favorite room. (Image: @nataliejeffcott).

Sure, your attic could be just the place where you store Christmas decorations the other 11 months of the year. But it could ALSO serve as a functional and usable space, like this attic-turned home office. Click the link in our bio for 4 more attic makeovers that might just inspire you to transform your space upstairs. (Image and Space: @unskinnyboppy).

The Oval Office is, well, the Oval Office. It pretty much looks the same no matter who is occupying it. It’s only after they’ve moved on from the White House that a president can really let their style shine. Which is why this Presidents Day, we are imagining the post-White House homes of some of the most famous television presidents—the good, the inept, and the murder-y. 
Jed Barlet once made all of Air Force One sing the Notre Dame Fight Song as they passed over South Bend, so his navy and gold color palette is no surprise here. OF COURSE, Fitz has a portrait of Olivia in his space. Selina Meyer's “Peace Summit Award” would definitely be on display in her home. No one has to know that it’s not a real Nobel Peace Prize, do they? And lastly, Claire (Underwood) Hale, would have ZERO patience for clutter or tchotchkes. Click the link in our bio to read more about each of these fictional presidential spaces. (Illustrations: @anahardesign).
Raise your hand if you are going to dream of this fridge tonight. ✋ (via @homebythestation).

When @jinajavier and her husband Jeff moved into their new home, they had to downsize. How did they do it? They turned to Marie Kondo, of course! Tidying up her home not only led to a simplified, more genuinely styled space for her and her family, but it is also gave Jina renewed clarity and the energy to start her next business venture. See her full, tidied up home, via the link in our bio. (Image: @hillary.halter)
